public class SimpleNodeProxy
extends NodeProxy

A node representing a state.

The states of a finite-state machine are represented as simple nodes in a graph, connected to each other by edges representing the state transitions. A simple node thus can be viewed as a point in a graph (GraphProxy) with edges (EdgeProxy) linking to it.

The information attached to a simple node is mostly used for rendering.

Name.
A string identifying the node.
Initial.
A boolean flag identifying whether the node represents an initial state or not. In a deterministic graph, the must be exactly one initial node.
Geometry information.
In addition, each node may have layout information to describe the node's position in the graph, and the placement of the label, i.e., the name string, relative to the node.

Author:
Robi Malik

equalsWithGeometry

public boolean equalsWithGeometry(Object partner)
Description copied from interface: Proxy
Checks whether two elements are equal and have the same geometry information. This method implements content-based equality, i.e., two elements will be equal if their contents are the same. While the standard equals() method only considers structural contents, this method also takes the layout information of graphical objects such as nodes and edges into account. This method can be very slow for large structures and is intended for testing purposes only.
